'''Obia''' (sohtaim spel ''Obi'', ''Obea'', ar ''Uobia''),<ref>Generally conceived as an adjective, it is frequently used as a noun, yet Obe or Obi is the noun substantive. Williams J, ''Voodoos and Obeahs: Phases of West Indian Witchcraft,'' (1932) Lincoln MacVeagh, Chapter:1 Origin of Obeah. The word ''obeah'' may be the feminine adjective of the substantive ''obi'', which signifies ''a charm''. Deane J, The Worship of the Serpent (1883) p.163.</ref> a toerm yuuz ina di [[Wes Indiz|Wes Indiz]] fi refa tu [[Fuok Majik|fuok majik]], [[Majik (paranaamal)|saasri]], ah rilijos praktis divelop mongx Wes Afrikan sliev, spisifikali a [[Odinani|Ibo]] arijin.<ref name=eltis>David Eltis and David Richardson (1997)[https://books.google.com/books?id=kuXEzQZQmawC&pg=PA88/ ''Routes to slavery: direction, ethnicity, and mortality in the transatlantic slave trade''] Routledge p. 88 ISBN 0-7146-4820-5</ref> Obia simila tu ada [[Afro-Amoerkan rilijan|Afro-Amoerkan rilijan]] ingkluudn [[Palo (rilijan)|Palo]], [[Ieshan Vuduu|Vuduu]], [[Santeriya|Santeriya]], ah [[Huuduu (fuok majik)|Huuduu]]. Obia praktis ina [[Surinam|Surinam]], [[Kyuuba|Kyuuba]], [[Jumieka|Jumieka]], [[Chrinidad ah Tubiego|Chrinidad ah Tubiego]], [[Daminiika|Daminiika]], [[Gayana|Gayana]], [[Grinieda|Grinieda]], [[Biliiz|Biliiz]], di [[Ba'aamaz|Ba'aamaz]], ah ada [[Kiaribiyan|Kiaribiyan]] nieshan.<ref name=Psy>Mario Incayawar, Ronald Wintrob, Lise Bouchard and Goffredo Bartocci |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Su9Zhe3HglsC&pg=PA222/ ''Psychiatrists and Traditional Healers: Unwitting Partners in Global Mental Health] JOHN wiley, 2009, ISBN 0-470-51683-6</ref>

Di toerm 'obeah' fos fain ina dakiument frah di hoerli 18t senchri, ina kanekshan tu [[Kwiin Nani a di Maruun|Nani a di Maruun]], bot diskoshan bouti eh-bikom muo friikuent wen deh meki iliigal ina Jumieka afta [[Taki Waar|Taki Waar]], wen wah obiaman provaid advais tu di rebldem.

Ina 1787 wah leta tu wah Ingglish nyuuzpiepa refa tu "Obiu-women" we intoerprit di wish a di ded a di fiunaral a wah sliev moerda ina Jumieka: wah futnuot explien se di toerm eh-miin "Waiz-uman".<ref>BECARA, i. e. White Man. "To the Editor of the Universal Register." Times, London, England, 23 Nov. 1787: 1. The Times Digital Archive. Akses 7 June 2012.</ref>

